-if realm.adjective == "affective"
  =render "affect"

%p The #{realm.adjective} realm runs on #{realm.energy}.
%p You use #{realm.energy} in order to #{realm.practice} and #{realm.accomplish_goals}. The more you #{realm.practice}, the more #{realm.energy} you need, whether or not you are trying to #{realm.accomplish} #{realm.anything}. The harder #{realm.goals} are to #{realm.accomplish}, the more #{realm.strength} you will develop while #{realm.practice.ing}. The more #{realm.strength} you develop, the more #{realm.energy} you need to fuel your #{realm.strength} when you do #{realm.practice}. Even if you aren’t #{realm.accomplish.ing} #{realm.anything}. If you don’t continually use and fuel your #{realm.strength}, it will atrophy.
%p In order to get #{realm.energy} you need to #{realm.take_resources}. It is difficult to #{realm.take_resources} you cannot #{realm.notice} or that #{realm.appear} bad. Most #{realm.resources} are a combination of #{realm.strengtheners} and #{realm.energizers}. #{realm.resources.capitalize} that are mostly #{realm.energizers} are easier to #{realm.take} and #{realm.collect} than those that are primarily #{realm.strengtheners}. But #{realm.strengtheners} #{realm.is_are} essential if you want to develop #{realm.strength}. If you #{realm.take} more #{realm.strengtheners} than you need, you won’t spontaneously build more #{realm.strength}, but if you #{realm.take} more #{realm.energizers} than you need, the excess #{realm.energy} will be stored as #{realm.reserves} for later use.
